SIMPLE: sedentary
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Sedentary
<hw>Sed"en*ta*ry</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>sedentarius</ets>, fr. <ets>sedere</ets> to sit: cf. F.
<ets>se⟦eacute⟧dentaire</ets>. See <er>Sedent</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>Accustomed to sit much or long; <as>as, a <ex>sedentary</ex>
man</as>.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Sedentary</xex>, scholastic sophists.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Bp. Warburton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Characterized by, or requiring, much sitting;
<as>as, a <ex>sedentary</ex> employment; a <ex>sedentary</ex>
life</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Any education that confined itself to <qex>sedentary</qex>
pursuits was essentially imperfect.</q>
<rj><qau>Beaconsfield.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Inactive; motionless; sluggish; hence, calm;
tranquil.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧The <xex>sedentary</xex>
earth.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The soul, considered abstractly from its passions, is of a remiss,
<qex>sedentary</qex> nature.</q> <rj><qau>Spectator.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Caused by long sitting.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Sedentary</xex> numbness.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Remaining in one place,
especially when firmly attached to some object; <as>as, the oyster is a
<ex>sedentary</ex> mollusk; the barnacles are <ex>sedentary</ex>
crustaceans</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Sedentary spider</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>one of
a tribe of spiders which rest motionless until their prey is caught in
their web.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sederunt</ent>⟦br⟧
\'d8
